    "text": "Below is a fully textual Data\u2010Flow\u2010Diagram description of every element in the picture, each classified as External Entity / Process / Data Store / Data Flow (and annotated with one primary STRIDE threat category), then a complete list of all the named connections between them, and finally a list of the trust\u2010boundary demarcations.\n\n1. ELEMENTS  \n1.1 External Entities  \n  \u2022 Anonymous User (External Entity) [STRIDE: Spoofing]  \n    \u2013 The attacker or end\u2010user on the public Internet who sends HTTP requests to the blog.  \n\n1.2 Processes  \n  \u2022 Blog Application (Process) [STRIDE: Tampering]  \n    \u2013 An Azure Function front\u2010end that accepts user requests (render pages, invoke API).  \n\n  \u2022 Authorization Logic (Process) [STRIDE: Repudiation]  \n    \u2013 The function code path that checks incoming user roles/permissions (green\u2010authorized vs red\u2010unauthorized).  \n\n  \u2022 Blog Application API (Process) [STRIDE: Tampering]  \n    \u2013 A separate Azure Function endpoint that performs data operations (CRUD) on blog content.  \n\n  \u2022 Development Instance (Process) [STRIDE: Denial of Service]  \n    \u2013 An Azure Container Instance that pulls build artifacts from Dev Storage Container and orchestrates deployments.  \n\n  \u2022 Automation Account (Process) [STRIDE: Elevation of Privilege]  \n    \u2013 An Azure Automation Account with Owner role on a resource group; runs scripts to provision or update resources.  \n\n1.3 Data Stores  \n  \u2022 Application Resource Storage Container (Data Store) [STRIDE: Information Disclosure]  \n    \u2013 Storage container holding application static assets and config used in the deployment pipeline.  \n\n  \u2022 Dev Storage Container (Data Store) [STRIDE: Information Disclosure]  \n    \u2013 The blob container where build artifacts are delivered for the Development Instance to consume.  \n\n  \u2022 Resource Group (Data Store) [STRIDE: Tampering]  \n    \u2013 Azure Resource Group containing the deployed blog application resources.  \n\n  \u2022 Function Code (Data Store) [STRIDE: Information Disclosure]  \n    \u2013 The actual .js/.csx function code files retrieved by the Blog Application API at runtime.  \n\n  \u2022 Credentials (Data Store) [STRIDE: Information Disclosure]  \n    \u2013 Secrets (connection strings, keys) stored in Azure Key Vault that the API fetches.  \n\n  \u2022 Storage Account (Data Store) [STRIDE: Information Disclosure]  \n    \u2013 Holds image and media assets for blog posts, used by both front\u2010end and API.  \n\n  \u2022 Cosmos DB (Data Store) [STRIDE: Denial of Service]  \n    \u2013 NoSQL database where all blog posts, comments, and metadata are persisted.  \n\n1.4 Data Flows  \n  (These will be named in the Connection section below.)\n\n2. CONNECTIONS (all are Data Flows unless otherwise noted)  \n2.1 User \u2192 Blog Application  \n  \u2013 HTTP GET/POST requests from the Internet to the front\u2010end function.  \n\n2.2 Blog Application \u2192 Application Resource Storage Container  \n  \u2013 Reads/Writes of static assets or configuration blobs.  \n\n2.3 Application Resource Storage Container \u2192 Dev Storage Container  \n  \u2013 The deployment pipeline copies artifacts from the app container into the dedicated Dev container.  \n\n2.4 Dev Storage Container \u2192 Development Instance  \n  \u2013 The container instance polls or is triggered by new blobs (build artifacts).  \n\n2.5 Development Instance \u2192 Automation Account  \n  \u2013 Contributor\u2010role API calls to kick off runbooks or scripts in Azure Automation.  \n\n2.6 Automation Account \u2192 Resource Group  \n  \u2013 Owner\u2010role actions to create/update resources (Function App, Key Vault, DB, etc.).  \n\n2.7 Resource Group \u2192 Anonymous User (compromise vector)  \n  \u2013 In the diagram the attacker eventually gains elevated rights in the Resource Group.  \n\n2.8 Blog Application \u2192 Authorization Logic  \n  \u2013 Internal invocation to validate the user\u2019s role/permissions.  \n\n2.9 Authorization Logic \u2192 Authorized (green) / Unauthorized (red)  \n  \u2013 Decision outcome branching: allow or deny.  \n\n2.10 Blog Application API \u2192 Function Code  \n  \u2013 Retrieval of the function runtime code (e.g. from a package store).  \n\n2.11 Blog Application API \u2192 Credentials  \n  \u2013 Key Vault lookup to get connection strings or keys.  \n\n2.12 Blog Application API \u2192 Storage Account  \n  \u2013 Blob storage operations for images, etc.  \n\n2.13 Blog Application API \u2192 Cosmos DB  \n  \u2013 Document queries/inserts/updates for blog content.  \n\n3. TRUST BOUNDARIES  \n  \u2022 Internet vs Blog Application  \n    \u2013 Boundary separating untrusted external users from the front\u2010end function.  \n\n  \u2022 Blog Application vs Azure Platform  \n    \u2013 The function runtime\u2019s trust zone boundary before reaching underlying storage and compute resources.  \n\n  \u2022 Dev Pipeline vs Production Resource Group  \n    \u2013 Isolates ephemeral Dev Storage Container & Container Instance from the live Resource Group where an attacker could escalate.  \n\n  \u2022 API vs Key Vault  \n    \u2013 The highly restricted enclave around secrets; only the API process may cross it to fetch credentials.",
