        {
            "role": "system",
            "content": "# Role and Objective\n\nYou are a **Threat Modeling expert** with 20 years of experience.\n\n## Your objectives are:\n- to provide user with relative information about cybersecurity threats;\n- to describe ways of mitigation for those threats;\n- to analyze user's systems and compile reports about threats within those systems;\n- to answer user questions regarding those reports.\n\n# Instructions\n- Always follow the provided output format for new messages.\n- Maintain a professional and concise tone in all responses.\n- Rely on data provided with the user's message whenever appropriate. Especially if it contains information regarding cybersecurity threats, mitigations, etc.\n- If you've resolved the user's request, ask if there's anything else you can help with.\n\n## Report generation\nWhen provided with the system description and report output format, think step-by-step:\n1. Analyze the provided system description.\n2. Perform comprehensive threat modeling according to the frameworks described lower.\n3. If you reach a limit of the response size and there is the **is_final** field in the provided output format, fill it with **False** to indicate that the report is incomplete.\n4. When asked to **CONTINUE**, carry on with the report. In this case use the message field for additional thinking.\n\n- Always identify ALL possible threats.\n- Multiple instances of the same threat type can exist across different system elements and connections.\n- Sometimes not all OWASP or MITRE threats may be present in the system.\n- Avoid generation of non-applicable threats.\n- List every threat separately for different elements, explain their specific context and risk level for that particular element.\n- Consider how threats affect both system components and their interactions (connections, APIs, data flows, etc.)\n- Always fill all the necessary fields unless otherwise stated.\n\n# Output Format\n- Use the following format for OWASP and MITRE threats:\n    **`<ThreatID>: <ThreatName>`**\n    For example:\n    - **A01:2021: Broken Access Control**\n    - **T1566: Phishing**\n\n# Threat model context\nUse the following threats for the corresponding threat models:\n\n\n## STRIDE:\nWhile generating threats use **STRIDE-per-Element** approach. Each element **must** contain threats according to the matrix, so fully cover it with relevant threats.\n\n### STRIDE Matrix:\nMatrix contains appropriate threat types for each element type.\nExternal Entity: Spoofing, Repudiation\nProcess: Spoofing, Tampering, Repudiation, Information Disclosure, Denial of Service, Elevation of Privileges\nData Flow: Tampering, Information Disclosure, Denial of Service\nData Store: Tampering, Repudiation, Information Disclosure, Denial of Service## OWASP Top 10 2021:\nA01:2021: Broken Access Control - Prevents users from acting outside permissions. Failures expose data or actions via bypasses, privilege escalation, or misconfigurations.\nA02:2021: Cryptographic Failures - Inadequate protection of sensitive data at rest or transit due to weak encryption, poor key management, or deprecated algorithms.\nA03:2021: Injection - Flaws allowing untrusted data to execute commands or queries. Common in SQL, NoSQL, OS, or LDAP when inputs aren\u0432\u0402\u2122t properly validated or sanitized.\nA04:2021: Insecure Design - Weak or missing security controls due to flawed design. Cannot be fixed by secure coding alone; needs proper threat modeling and controls.\nA05:2021: Security Misconfiguration - Improper settings, default credentials, or unnecessary features leave systems exposed. Requires consistent hardening and patching.\nA06:2021: Vulnerable and Outdated Components - Using unsupported, unpatched libraries or frameworks exposes systems to known exploits. Maintain inventory and updates.\nA07:2021: Identification and Authentication Failures - Weak authentication allows account hijacking via brute force, default creds, poor session management, or missing MFA.\nA08:2021: Software and Data Integrity Failures - Trusting unverified code, plugins, or updates risks malicious tampering. Secure CI/CD pipelines and integrity checks are key.\nA09:2021: Security Logging and Monitoring Failures - Inadequate logging and alerting prevent breach detection and response. Audit critical events and monitor suspicious actions.\nA10:2021: Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF) - Improper URL validation lets attackers force servers to fetch internal or external resources, bypassing network protections.\nFor MITRE ATT&CK categorization use valid MITRE ATT&CK techniques.\n\n\n\n# Reasoning Steps\nFirst, think carefully step by step about the user's system, elements, connections and applicable threats. Then, construct a report."
        },
        {
            "role": "user",
            "content": "Below is a fully textual Data\u2010Flow\u2010Diagram description of every element in the picture, each classified as External Entity / Process / Data Store / Data Flow (and annotated with one primary STRIDE threat category), then a complete list of all the named connections between them, and finally a list of the trust\u2010boundary demarcations.\n\n1. ELEMENTS  \n1.1 External Entities  \n  \u2022 Anonymous User (External Entity) [STRIDE: Spoofing]  \n    \u2013 The attacker or end\u2010user on the public Internet who sends HTTP requests to the blog.  \n\n1.2 Processes  \n  \u2022 Blog Application (Process) [STRIDE: Tampering]  \n    \u2013 An Azure Function front\u2010end that accepts user requests (render pages, invoke API).  \n\n  \u2022 Authorization Logic (Process) [STRIDE: Repudiation]  \n    \u2013 The function code path that checks incoming user roles/permissions (green\u2010authorized vs red\u2010unauthorized).  \n\n  \u2022 Blog Application API (Process) [STRIDE: Tampering]  \n    \u2013 A separate Azure Function endpoint that performs data operations (CRUD) on blog content.  \n\n  \u2022 Development Instance (Process) [STRIDE: Denial of Service]  \n    \u2013 An Azure Container Instance that pulls build artifacts from Dev Storage Container and orchestrates deployments.  \n\n  \u2022 Automation Account (Process) [STRIDE: Elevation of Privilege]  \n    \u2013 An Azure Automation Account with Owner role on a resource group; runs scripts to provision or update resources.  \n\n1.3 Data Stores  \n  \u2022 Application Resource Storage Container (Data Store) [STRIDE: Information Disclosure]  \n    \u2013 Storage container holding application static assets and config used in the deployment pipeline.  \n\n  \u2022 Dev Storage Container (Data Store) [STRIDE: Information Disclosure]  \n    \u2013 The blob container where build artifacts are delivered for the Development Instance to consume.  \n\n  \u2022 Resource Group (Data Store) [STRIDE: Tampering]  \n    \u2013 Azure Resource Group containing the deployed blog application resources.  \n\n  \u2022 Function Code (Data Store) [STRIDE: Information Disclosure]  \n    \u2013 The actual .js/.csx function code files retrieved by the Blog Application API at runtime.  \n\n  \u2022 Credentials (Data Store) [STRIDE: Information Disclosure]  \n    \u2013 Secrets (connection strings, keys) stored in Azure Key Vault that the API fetches.  \n\n  \u2022 Storage Account (Data Store) [STRIDE: Information Disclosure]  \n    \u2013 Holds image and media assets for blog posts, used by both front\u2010end and API.  \n\n  \u2022 Cosmos DB (Data Store) [STRIDE: Denial of Service]  \n    \u2013 NoSQL database where all blog posts, comments, and metadata are persisted.  \n\n1.4 Data Flows  \n  (These will be named in the Connection section below.)\n\n2. CONNECTIONS (all are Data Flows unless otherwise noted)  \n2.1 User \u2192 Blog Application  \n  \u2013 HTTP GET/POST requests from the Internet to the front\u2010end function.  \n\n2.2 Blog Application \u2192 Application Resource Storage Container  \n  \u2013 Reads/Writes of static assets or configuration blobs.  \n\n2.3 Application Resource Storage Container \u2192 Dev Storage Container  \n  \u2013 The deployment pipeline copies artifacts from the app container into the dedicated Dev container.  \n\n2.4 Dev Storage Container \u2192 Development Instance  \n  \u2013 The container instance polls or is triggered by new blobs (build artifacts).  \n\n2.5 Development Instance \u2192 Automation Account  \n  \u2013 Contributor\u2010role API calls to kick off runbooks or scripts in Azure Automation.  \n\n2.6 Automation Account \u2192 Resource Group  \n  \u2013 Owner\u2010role actions to create/update resources (Function App, Key Vault, DB, etc.).  \n\n2.7 Resource Group \u2192 Anonymous User (compromise vector)  \n  \u2013 In the diagram the attacker eventually gains elevated rights in the Resource Group.  \n\n2.8 Blog Application \u2192 Authorization Logic  \n  \u2013 Internal invocation to validate the user\u2019s role/permissions.  \n\n2.9 Authorization Logic \u2192 Authorized (green) / Unauthorized (red)  \n  \u2013 Decision outcome branching: allow or deny.  \n\n2.10 Blog Application API \u2192 Function Code  \n  \u2013 Retrieval of the function runtime code (e.g. from a package store).  \n\n2.11 Blog Application API \u2192 Credentials  \n  \u2013 Key Vault lookup to get connection strings or keys.  \n\n2.12 Blog Application API \u2192 Storage Account  \n  \u2013 Blob storage operations for images, etc.  \n\n2.13 Blog Application API \u2192 Cosmos DB  \n  \u2013 Document queries/inserts/updates for blog content.  \n\n3. TRUST BOUNDARIES  \n  \u2022 Internet vs Blog Application  \n    \u2013 Boundary separating untrusted external users from the front\u2010end function.  \n\n  \u2022 Blog Application vs Azure Platform  \n    \u2013 The function runtime\u2019s trust zone boundary before reaching underlying storage and compute resources.  \n\n  \u2022 Dev Pipeline vs Production Resource Group  \n    \u2013 Isolates ephemeral Dev Storage Container & Container Instance from the live Resource Group where an attacker could escalate.  \n\n  \u2022 API vs Key Vault  \n    \u2013 The highly restricted enclave around secrets; only the API process may cross it to fetch credentials."
        },
        {
            "role": "assistant",
            "content": "{\"message\":\"I\u2019ve performed an initial STRIDE\u2010per\u2010element analysis for your Azure\u2010based blog scenario. Below are the first set of identified threats covering External Entities, core Processes, and the first Data Flow. Each threat includes STRIDE category, MITRE ATT&CK mapping, OWASP Top 10 mapping (where applicable), a brief mitigation, and a representative CVSS 3.1 vector. Let me know when you\u2019d like me to continue through all remaining elements and flows.\",\"threats\":[{\"id\":1,\"element\":\"Anonymous User\",\"threat_description\":\"Attacker spoofs a legitimate user\u2019s identity to bypass access controls.\",\"element_type\":\"External Entity\",\"stride\":\"Spoofing\",\"Mitre ATT&CK\":\"T1078: Valid Accounts\",\"OWASP Top 10\":\"A07:2021\",\"mitigation\":\"Enforce strong authentication (MFA, unique credentials) and monitor for anomalous login behavior.\",\"cvss_vector\":\"AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:L/I:L/A:N\"},{\"id\":2,\"element\":\"Anonymous User\",\"threat_description\":\"Attacker disputes or denies actions taken (e.g. malicious changes) to evade accountability.\",\"element_type\":\"External Entity\",\"stride\":\"Repudiation\",\"Mitre ATT&CK\":\"T1563: Remote Service Session Hijacking\",\"OWASP Top 10\":\"A09:2021\",\"mitigation\":\"Implement robust logging with cryptographic non-repudiation (digitally signed logs) and time stamps.\",\"cvss_vector\":\"AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:N/I:N/A:N\"},{\"id\":3,\"element\":\"Blog Application\",\"threat_description\":\"Unauthorized actor invokes API endpoints under a spoofed session token.\",\"element_type\":\"Process\",\"stride\":\"Spoofing\",\"Mitre ATT&CK\":\"T1550: Use of Valid Accounts\",\"OWASP Top 10\":\"A07:2021\",\"mitigation\":\"Validate and bind session tokens to user context; rotate and expire tokens frequently.\",\"cvss_vector\":\"AV:N/AC:L/PR:L/UI:N/S:U/C:H/I:H/A:L\"},{\"id\":4,\"element\":\"Blog Application\",\"threat_description\":\"Attacker tampers with HTTP request parameters to elevate privileges or change data.\",\"element_type\":\"Process\",\"stride\":\"Tampering\",\"Mitre ATT&CK\":\"T1490: Inhibit System Recovery\",\"OWASP Top 10\":\"A01:2021\",\"mitigation\":\"Validate and sanitize all input; implement parameterized requests and payload integrity checks.\",\"cvss_vector\":\"AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:H/I:H/A:N\"},{\"id\":5,\"element\":\"Blog Application\",\"threat_description\":\"Lack of reliable audit trail allows user to deny having performed an action.\",\"element_type\":\"Process\",\"stride\":\"Repudiation\",\"Mitre ATT&CK\":\"T1071: Application Layer Protocol\",\"OWASP Top 10\":\"A09:2021\",\"mitigation\":\"Ensure detailed, immutable audit logs with unique user identifiers and time stamps.\",\"cvss_vector\":\"AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:N/I:N/A:N\"},{\"id\":6,\"element\":\"Blog Application\",\"threat_description\":\"Error messages leak stack traces or config details, exposing sensitive info.\",\"element_type\":\"Process\",\"stride\":\"Information Disclosure\",\"Mitre ATT&CK\":\"T1552: Unsecured Credentials\",\"OWASP Top 10\":\"A05:2021\",\"mitigation\":\"Return generic error pages; disable debug information in production.\",\"cvss_vector\":\"AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:L/I:N/A:N\"},{\"id\":7,\"element\":\"Blog Application\",\"threat_description\":\"High volume of HTTP requests overwhelms the function, causing downtime.\",\"element_type\":\"Process\",\"stride\":\"Denial of Service\",\"Mitre ATT&CK\":\"T1499: Endpoint Denial of Service\",\"OWASP Top 10\":null,\"mitigation\":\"Implement rate limiting, WAF, and autoscaling with throttling policies.\",\"cvss_vector\":\"AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:N/S:C/C:N/I:N/A:H\"},{\"id\":8,\"element\":\"Blog Application\",\"threat_description\":\"Misconfigured Azure RBAC allows attacker to elevate privileges via function settings.\",\"element_type\":\"Process\",\"stride\":\"Elevation of Privilege\",\"Mitre ATT&CK\":\"T1548: Abuse Elevation Control Mechanism\",\"OWASP Top 10\":\"A05:2021\",\"mitigation\":\"Apply least-privilege principles; restrict function app managed identity permissions.\",\"cvss_vector\":\"AV:N/AC:L/PR:H/UI:N/S:U/C:N/I:N/A:N\"},{\"id\":9,\"element\":\"Authorization Logic\",\"threat_description\":\"An attacker forges user claims to bypass role checks.\",\"element_type\":\"Process\",\"stride\":\"Spoofing\",\"Mitre ATT&CK\":\"T1556: Modify Authentication Process\",\"OWASP Top 10\":\"A07:2021\",\"mitigation\":\"Cryptographically validate JWT claims; enforce server-side role checks.\",\"cvss_vector\":\"AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:H/I:H/A:N\"},{\"id\":10,\"element\":\"Authorization Logic\",\"threat_description\":\"Logic tampering via code injection alters permission evaluation.\",\"element_type\":\"Process\",\"stride\":\"Tampering\",\"Mitre ATT&CK\":\"T1059: Command and Scripting Interpreter\",\"OWASP Top 10\":\"A03:2021\",\"mitigation\":\"Use secure coding practices; perform code-review and fine-grained input validation.\",\"cvss_vector\":\"AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:H/I:H/A:N\"},{\"id\":11,\"element\":\"Authorization Logic\",\"threat_description\":\"Insufficient logging of authorization decisions allows repudiation of grant/deny actions.\",\"element_type\":\"Process\",\"stride\":\"Repudiation\",\"Mitre ATT&CK\":\"T1078: Valid Accounts\",\"OWASP Top 10\":\"A09:2021\",\"mitigation\":\"Log all authorization attempts with user ID, timestamp, and outcome.\",\"cvss_vector\":\"AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:N/I:N/A:N\"},{\"id\":12,\"element\":\"Authorization Logic\",\"threat_description\":\"Debug endpoints expose user roles or policy logic.\",\"element_type\":\"Process\",\"stride\":\"Information Disclosure\",\"Mitre ATT&CK\":\"T1614: Archive Collected Data\",\"OWASP Top 10\":\"A05:2021\",\"mitigation\":\"Remove or secure any debug/diagnostic endpoints; enforce auth on admin APIs.\",\"cvss_vector\":\"AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:L/I:N/A:N\"},{\"id\":13,\"element\":\"Authorization Logic\",\"threat_description\":\"Heavy role\u2010check loops can be abused to slow service or cause crashes.\",\"element_type\":\"Process\",\"stride\":\"Denial of Service\",\"Mitre ATT&CK\":\"T1499: Endpoint Denial of Service\",\"OWASP Top 10\":null,\"mitigation\":\"Limit recursion; cache role mappings; apply execution timeouts.\",\"cvss_vector\":\"AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:N/I:N/A:H\"},{\"id\":14,\"element\":\"Authorization Logic\",\"threat_description\":\"Privilege escalation through misconfigured policy giving admin rights.\",\"element_type\":\"Process\",\"stride\":\"Elevation of Privilege\",\"Mitre ATT&CK\":\"T1548.003: Abuse Elevation Control Mechanism: Windows Management Instrumentation\",\"OWASP Top 10\":\"A05:2021\",\"mitigation\":\"Review policy definitions; enforce separation of duty and RBAC least privilege.\",\"cvss_vector\":\"AV:N/AC:L/PR:H/UI:N/S:U/C:N/I:N/A:N\"},{\"id\":15,\"element\":\"User \u2192 Blog Application\",\"threat_description\":\"Malicious interception and modification of HTTP requests in transit.\",\"element_type\":\"Data Flow\",\"stride\":\"Tampering\",\"Mitre ATT&CK\":\"T1557: Adversary-in-the-Middle\",\"OWASP Top 10\":\"A02:2021\",\"mitigation\":\"Enforce TLS 1.2+ with HSTS and certificate pinning where possible.\",\"cvss_vector\":\"AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:H/I:H/A:N\"},{\"id\":16,\"element\":\"User \u2192 Blog Application\",\"threat_description\":\"Eavesdropping on unencrypted HTTP traffic exposes session tokens.\",\"element_type\":\"Data Flow\",\"stride\":\"Information Disclosure\",\"Mitre ATT&CK\":\"T1040: Network Sniffing\",\"OWASP Top 10\":\"A02:2021\",\"mitigation\":\"Use HTTPS exclusively; disable HTTP; enable Perfect Forward Secrecy.\",\"cvss_vector\":\"AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:H/I:N/A:N\"},{\"id\":17,\"element\":\"User \u2192 Blog Application\",\"threat_description\":\"Flooding the front-end with requests to exhaust resources.\",\"element_type\":\"Data Flow\",\"stride\":\"Denial of Service\",\"Mitre ATT&CK\":\"T1499.001: Endpoint Flood\",\"OWASP Top 10\":null,\"mitigation\":\"Implement WAF rules, rate limiting, and CAPTCHA on forms.\",\"cvss_vector\":\"AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:N/S:C/C:N/I:N/A:H\"}],\"is_final\":false}"
